%N A393845 a(n) is the smallest positive multiple of n whose decimal representation contains every distinct digit of n-1.
%C A393845 It looks as if most terms would be even, but asymptotically almost all numbers n are pandigital, in which case a(n) = n. Therefore, the fraction of odd terms in a(1)..a(n) gets arbitrarily close to 50%. (It grows to 33% near 2*10^6 and to 35% near 2*10^7.) - _M. F. Hasler_, Apr 02 2026
%e A393845 a(14) = 1036 because 13 has digits {1, 3}, and 1036 is the smallest multiple of 14 containing both digits.
%t A393845 a[n_]:=Module[{k=n},While[!SubsetQ[IntegerDigits[k],IntegerDigits[n-1]], k+=n]; k]; Array[a,54] (* _Stefano Spezia_, Apr 02 2026 *)
%o A393845 (Python)
%o A393845 from itertools import count
%o A393845 def a(n):
%o A393845     s = set(str(n-1))
%o A393845     return next(m for m in count(n, n) if s - set(str(m)) == set())
%o A393845 print([a(n) for n in range(1, 55)]) # _Michael S. Branicky_, Apr 01 2026
%o A393845 (PARI) apply( {A393845(n,d=Set(digits(n-1)))=n>1&&forstep(k=n,oo,n, #setminus(d, Set(digits(k)))||return(k));10}, [1..99]) \\ _M. F. Hasler_, Apr 02 2026
